  "original_title": "\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc6\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0b9f\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbe\u0ba9 \u0bb5\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bc0\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b85\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Increase in interest rates for credit cards",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "Many commercial banks in Sri Lanka have raised interest rates on credit cards, according to a central bank report.",
        "Accordingly, some commercial banks have announced a 30 percent interest rate on their credit cards.",
        "Credit card interest rates have risen from 18% to 24% following the announcement by the Monetary Board of the Central Bank of Sri Lanka on April 8 that it would remove the maximum interest rate cap on credit cards. In this case, the interest rate is currently reported to have risen to 30%.",
        "According to the latest reports of the Central Bank of Sri Lanka, the total number of credit cards in operation in the country at the end of April this year (2022) was 1,973,481. By the end of April (2022) the total amount for these credit cards will be Rs. 138,192 million.",
        "Similarly, in the first four months of this year, the number of active (national) credit cards in the country stood at 46,286 and the total balance of these credit cards stood at 4.9 billion EHUs."
      ],
